Kim Jong Il's Songun Leadership Praised in Indonesia 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 29 (KCNA) -- The Songun leadership of  Kim Jong Il provides a sure guarantee for the building of a great prosperous powerful nation, a new turning point in socialist construction, said the chairman of the Indonesian Marine Transport Trade Union in a statement on Mar. 24 on the occasion of the 13th anniversary of Kim Jong Il's election as chairman of the DPRK National Defence Commission.
 Recalling that the Korean people have reliably defended socialism and achieved great successes in the building of a great prosperous powerful nation under the wise leadership of Kim Jong Il over the last more than one decade, he continued:
 Kim Jong Il is a great politician leading the Korean people to victory with his Songun politics and by dint of the single-minded unity based on it. nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK has defended its sovereignty, reacting to the hard-line of outside forces with a tougher stand. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 We are sure that the DPRK will always emerge victorious under the leadership of Kim Jong Il.

U.S.-S. Korea Joint Military Exercises Denounced 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 29 (KCNA) -- The RSOI and Foal Eagle joint military exercises against the DPRK launched by the U.S. imperialists together with the south Korean military bellicose forces on Mar. 25 are a grave challenge to the desire of the people at home and abroad for peace and stability of the Korean Peninsula, and they are driving the situation in the region to the brink of confrontation and war.
 Rodong Sinmun Wednesday says this in a signed commentary.
 Denouncing them as very reckless and dangerous war drills which destroy the process of dialogue for settlement of the nuclear issue between the DPRK and the U.S. and pose a grave threat to the security of the Korean nation and the cause of Korea's reunification, the commentary says: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S., in its recent "national security strategy report", pulled up the dignified DPRK again, revealing its scheme to mount a preemptive attack upon the latter.
 At present, the conflict and friction between the DPRK and the U.S. over  the six-party talks for solving the nuclear issue are not likely to be settled but are growing more serious. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. has laid artificial obstacles to the talks under the absurd pretext while staging the war gambles against the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The situation is growing tenser than ever before and the prospect of peace and denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula appears remote due to the persistent anti-DPRK policy of the U.S. and its moves for a war. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Nevertheless, the south Korean bellicose forces are recklessly toeing the U.S. line.
 Aggression troops do not distinguish the north from the south in using nukes and, accordingly, to follow them is as good as inviting a nuclear disaster.
 The DPRK has clarified more than once that the right to a preemptive attack is not a monopoly of the U.S. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. imperialists and the south Korean bellicose forces would be well advised to clearly understand the will of the DPRK and behave with discretion.

Koreans in U.S. Demand Stop to Expansion of U.S. Military Base in S. Korea 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 29 (KCNA) -- We can never pardon the U.S. moves for the expansion of its military base in Phyongthaek and the south Korean "government's" land expropriation for it in Phyongthaek. 
 The Association of Koreans in Americas, the Federation of Koreans in Americas for Independence, Democracy and Reunification, the Solidarity of Koreans for Peace in the U.S. and other organizations said this in a statement on Mar. 24 in support of the south Korean people's struggle against the expansion of the U.S. military base in Phyongthaek. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Calling upon all the fellow countrymen at home and abroad to check the moves for the expansion of the U.S. military base in Phyongthaek and achieve the independent reunification and peace of the Korean Peninsula with their united struggle, the statement expressed full support to the residents in Phyongthaek and members of the civic and public organizations in their struggle. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The statement strongly demanded the Bush administration immediately stop its moves for the expansion of the U.S. military base in Phyongthaek and withdraw the U.S. troops from south Korea and the south Korean "government" authorities stop land expropriation at once.

Great King of Cambodia Hosts Reception 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 29 (KCNA) -- Great King of Cambodia Norodom Sihanouk on a visit to the DPRK hosted a film show and a reception on Mar. 28.
 On hand were the great king and queen, Cambodian guests and Chhorn Hay, Cambodian ambassador to the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The great king in a speech prior to the film show extended the most wholehearted thanks to leader Kim Jong Il for helping them produce the film during their visit to the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The film shows the development of the DPRK which has been beautifully changed, the great king said. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The participants appreciated Cambodian films including feature film "Recovery" made by the great king. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Then followed the reception, which was addressed by the great king and Yang Hyong Sop, vice-president of the Presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly.
 Present on invitation were Kim Yong Il, vice-minister of Foreign Affairs, and others.

Japan Urged to Make Proper Option 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 29 (KCNA) -- The Liberal Democratic Party of Japan on March 17 approved a "bill on  human  rights  situation  in north Korea" and decided to bring it up for discussion at the Diet within this month.  The bill calls on the government to compulsorily apply "economic sanctions against north Korea" in case of no progress in the settlement of the "abduction issue". 
  Meanwhile, the Japanese government called a meeting of leading officials of six ministries and agencies such as the Financial Service Agency, the National Police Agency and the Ministry of Economy and Industry on March 15 which discussed the issue of strictly controlling "remittance and export to north Korea."
 Minju Joson today observes in a signed commentary in this regard:
   The Japanese reactionaries are keen to suffocate the DPRK economically in a bid to achieve their objective. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Their behavior clearly suggests their ulterior intention to use an economic lever to do harm to the DPRK. Nothing is more base and disgusting than this folly prompted by a way of thinking of a political dwarf. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Japan seems to consider economic sanctions as principal leverage for pursuing its policy toward the DPRK though it does not care much. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Japan must be aware that over the last several decades the DPRK has pushed forward the construction of independent national economy as the basic line of socialist economic construction. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Japanese reactionaries are so foolish as to calculate that their application of economic sanctions against the DPRK would bring about a dramatic change there. This, however, only betrays their serious weak point as they are utterly ignorant of the trend of the times. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Japanese reactionaries would be well advised to make a proper option, cogitating about whether their confrontation with the DPRK in all areas would do Japan good.

King Kongmin's Mausoleum, Stone Sculpture Museum
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 29 (KCNA) -- The mausoleum of King Kongmin in Kaesong City, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea is one of the typical cultural heritages of the Korean nation.
 Kongmin was the 31st king of Koryo (918-1392). The mausoleum is biggest among the tombs of the successive kings of Koryo and was built with much labor. It represents the form of mausoleums in the closing years of Koryo. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The mausoleum consists of twin stone tombs, one for the king in the west and the other for the queen in the east. It is surrounded by various kinds of stone sculptures. It, therefore, is called "stone sculpture museum". &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The rectangular compound of the mausoleum is treble-terraced and elongated from east to west. It is approached up a slope by broad stairs. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The upper terrace is 40 meters from east to west and 24 meters from north to south. In the center of the terrace, there are the twin tombs, each standing on the dodecagon stone foundation. The grave mound is about 6.5 meters high and 13.7 meters in diameter. Each grave mound is surrounded at the bottom with wall-like stones on which 12 spirits of terrain including mouse, cow, tiger and rabbit are engraved in relief. 
 There are four statues of civil officials on the middle terrace and four statutes of military officers on the third terrace with two at the end of each side.
 The statues, about 3.3 meters high, evoke most convincingly the characters that they represent. Their open air setting makes them particularly effective. In bold relief against the mountains looming in the background, they look quite majestic. They are excellent ones among existing old stone sculptures in Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 After looking round the statues, a foreign historian said: it is wonderful that in the Middle Ages, Europeans used marble as the basic material of stone sculpture but Koryo people created such delicate statues with granite solider than marble as the basic material.

Japanese Authorities' Suppression of Chongryon Blasted
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 29 (KCNA) -- The public security department of the Tokyo Police Agency mobilized riot police on Mar. 23 to search six places including the Office of the Osaka Prefectural Korean Federation of Workers in Commerce in Japan, Koreans' houses and shops run by them.
 A spokesman for the DPRK-Japan Friendship Association in a statement Wednesday accused the Tokyo Police Agency of having worked hard to charge the General Association of Korean Residents in Japan (Chongryon) with an involvement in what it called "abduction case." It charged even a Korean restaurant owner in Japan with a "conspiracy in the abduction case" in a desperate bid to build up public opinion supporting its claim. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The statement continued: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The agency's action was a totally unreasonable provocation intended to meet its sinister political purpose of covering up the crimes Japan perpetrated in the past by inflicting untold misfortune and disasters upon the Koreans, linking the "abduction issue" to Chongryon and putting pressure upon the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is beyond doubt that the search was carried out at the instruction of the Japanese government authorities. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is a well-known fact that the authorities have escalated their campaign against the DPRK and Chongryon since they set up a "law enforcement team" and an "intelligence gathering committee" within a "special team to handle the abduction issue" under the supervision of the Cabinet secretariat. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Japanese authorities are becoming evermore undisguised in their suppression and restrictions on Chongryon and Koreans in Japan as evidenced by their unwarranted pressure upon them to pay fixed property tax and such blatant infringement upon the rights of Koreans in Japan by the Immigration Office as preventing them from leaving and reentering Japan. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 If the authorities truly stand for the DPRK-Japan friendship and the normalization of bilateral relations they should immediately stop all forms of suppression of tormenting and threatening Chongryon and Koreans in Japan. They should, at the same time, fully grant them their status as Koreans in Japan and satisfactorily guarantee Chongryon its legitimate activities in the basic spirit of the DPRK-Japan Pyongyang Declaration.
 We strongly urge the Japanese authorities to take an appropriate measure to prevent the repetition of a similar case.
